WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.670 --> 00:00:05.982
<i>♪ Thank you for being a friend</i>

2
00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:10.387
<i>♪ Traveled down the
road and back again</i>

3
00:00:10.411 --> 00:00:12.456
<i>♪ Your heart is true</i>

4
00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.414
<i>♪ You're a pal and a confidante</i>

5
00:00:17.418 --> 00:00:20.463
<i>♪ And if you threw a party</i>

6
00:00:20.487 --> 00:00:25.802
<i>♪ Invited everyone you knew</i>

7
00:00:25.826 --> 00:00:30.239
<i>♪ You would see the
biggest gift would be from me</i>

8
00:00:30.263 --> 00:00:32.209
<i>♪ And the card
attached would say</i>

9
00:00:32.233 --> 00:00:38.871
<i>♪ "Thank you for
being a friend" ♪</i>

10
00:00:59.426 --> 00:01:00.726
Thanks. honey.

11
00:01:01.729 --> 00:01:03.707
Girls. you will never guess

12
00:01:03.731 --> 00:01:05.709
who I just got off
the phone with.

13
00:01:05.733 --> 00:01:07.810
Trudy McMann. your best
friend from high school.

14
00:01:07.834 --> 00:01:10.101
She's coming to Miami for
your high-school reunion.

15
00:01:14.875 --> 00:01:17.721
Sophia. that's incredible.
You must have ESP.

16
00:01:17.745 --> 00:01:21.391
No. I have a phone
extension in my bedroom.

17
00:01:21.415 --> 00:01:23.426
Ma. how many times
do I have to tell you

18
00:01:23.450 --> 00:01:26.696
not to listen in on
my conversations?

19
00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:28.998
About twice a year.

20
00:01:29.022 --> 00:01:31.201
Like your phone is
ringing off the hook.

21
00:01:31.225 --> 00:01:33.669
Like you got such a
full social calendar.

22
00:01:33.693 --> 00:01:38.375
You're the only person who
ever got a refund on call waiting.

23
00:01:38.399 --> 00:01:40.644
All right. Ma. all right.

24
00:01:40.668 --> 00:01:43.280
Dorothy. high-school
reunions can be so much fun.

25
00:01:43.304 --> 00:01:45.282
I will never forget mine.

26
00:01:45.306 --> 00:01:47.884
I was the most
successful person there.

27
00:01:47.908 --> 00:01:51.788
Blanche. didn't you go to school with that
brilliant doctor who won the Nobel Prize?

28
00:01:51.812 --> 00:01:54.691
Oh. yes. but she let
her looks go to hell.

29
00:01:54.715 --> 00:01:57.460
You do sound excited. Dorothy.

30
00:01:57.484 --> 00:01:58.828
Well. I am. I am.

31
00:01:58.852 --> 00:02:02.265
But mostly it's about
seeing Trudy again.

32
00:02:02.289 --> 00:02:05.401
A girl never had a better
friend than Trudy McMann.

33
00:02:05.425 --> 00:02:07.604
What. Ma?

34
00:02:07.628 --> 00:02:11.296
Oh. nothing. My underwear
just hiked up on me.

35
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.878
Right while you were lying.

36
00:02:14.902 --> 00:02:18.281
Ly - Why do you say I'm lying?

37
00:02:18.305 --> 00:02:21.218
"A girl never had a better
friend than Trudy McMann"?

38
00:02:21.242 --> 00:02:24.488
Somebody here doesn't
remember prom night. 1946.

39
00:02:24.512 --> 00:02:25.689
Why? What happened?

40
00:02:25.713 --> 00:02:28.425
I don't know. I'm that somebody.

41
00:02:28.449 --> 00:02:32.495
No. I think what
Ma is referring to...

42
00:02:32.519 --> 00:02:35.665
is a little practical joke
that Trudy played on me.

43
00:02:35.689 --> 00:02:37.700
All of us on the tennis team

44
00:02:37.724 --> 00:02:41.338
decided that we would wear
our tennis whites to the prom.

45
00:02:41.362 --> 00:02:44.307
Well. I showed up.
and I was the only one.

46
00:02:44.331 --> 00:02:45.808
Oh. no!

47
00:02:45.832 --> 00:02:48.044
Your date must
have been horrified.

48
00:02:48.068 --> 00:02:52.137
No. Her brother was a
really good sport about it.

49
00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:55.619
No. Trudy and I played
a lot of practical jokes

50
00:02:55.643 --> 00:02:56.953
on each other.

51
00:02:56.977 --> 00:03:00.257
It was all part of a
happy. healthy rivalry.

52
00:03:00.281 --> 00:03:04.661
Oh. I was the butt of all
kinds of jokes growing up.

53
00:03:04.685 --> 00:03:06.730
Actually. it ran in the family.

54
00:03:06.754 --> 00:03:09.699
In our breakfast room.
we had one whole wall

55
00:03:09.723 --> 00:03:12.757
covered with "kick me"
signs we had collected.

56
00:03:14.928 --> 00:03:17.740
Oh. there was a story
attached to each one of them.

57
00:03:17.764 --> 00:03:21.032
And in some cases.
the original Scotch tape.

58
00:03:26.907 --> 00:03:29.686
So when's Trudy coming?

59
00:03:29.710 --> 00:03:33.356
Uh... week after next.

60
00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:35.591
Which reminds
me. I have to rush.

61
00:03:35.615 --> 00:03:37.627
Where to? Tennis lessons.

62
00:03:37.651 --> 00:03:40.863
I figure. if she's gonna be here.
we ought to have a nice. quiet game.

63
00:03:40.887 --> 00:03:42.932
Oh. that's sweet.
And a lot of crap.

64
00:03:42.956 --> 00:03:45.902
I'm gonna mop
the court with her.

65
00:03:45.926 --> 00:03:49.773
Oh. my. Looks like our
Dorothy still holds a grudge.

66
00:03:49.797 --> 00:03:52.976
'Course she holds a grudge.
We Sicilians are good at that.

67
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:54.911
That. and holding a grudge.

68
00:03:54.935 --> 00:03:57.480
Sophia. you said
"holding a grudge" twice.

69
00:03:57.504 --> 00:04:01.005
Hey. if you're good at
something. you brag about it.

70
00:04:06.847 --> 00:04:09.158
I am so excited.

71
00:04:09.182 --> 00:04:13.396
I can't believe I'm going to see
Trudy again after all these years.

72
00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:15.432
I'm excited for
you. too. Dorothy.

73
00:04:15.456 --> 00:04:17.467
That's why I want
everything perfect.

74
00:04:17.491 --> 00:04:19.502
I'm making Scandinavia's

75
00:04:19.526 --> 00:04:21.905
oldest and most
traditional appetizer treat -

76
00:04:21.929 --> 00:04:23.973
cheese and crackers.

77
00:04:23.997 --> 00:04:26.042
Cheese and crackers. Rose?

78
00:04:26.066 --> 00:04:28.767
Not eggs gafloofen?

79
00:04:31.838 --> 00:04:33.371
Ham and gunterhoggins?

80
00:04:35.742 --> 00:04:37.976
Pigs in a svenkabluden?

81
00:04:39.513 --> 00:04:44.015
No. but you sure know how
to make a girl's mouth water.

82
00:04:46.019 --> 00:04:47.919
Oh. my God. That's her.

83
00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:53.236
I sure hope time has
been good to Trudy.

84
00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:56.373
Good. not great.

85
00:04:56.397 --> 00:04:58.241
Oh. Trudy.

86
00:04:58.265 --> 00:05:06.149
Dorothy. Oh...
It's been so long.

87
00:05:06.173 --> 00:05:08.339
Boy. you look...

88
00:05:09.409 --> 00:05:11.142
It's been so long.

89
00:05:12.813 --> 00:05:15.558
I know. and you - you
look exactly the way you did

90
00:05:15.582 --> 00:05:17.893
at our high-school graduation.

91
00:05:17.917 --> 00:05:21.237
'Course. rumors were that you
were three months' pregnant.

92
00:05:22.089 --> 00:05:24.000
I want you to meet
my husband Jack.

93
00:05:24.024 --> 00:05:27.037
You didn't tell me you had
such a handsome husband.

94
00:05:27.061 --> 00:05:29.138
Didn't tell you he
was rich. either.

95
00:05:29.162 --> 00:05:31.141
That's my Trudy.

96
00:05:31.165 --> 00:05:34.077
You haven't lost
your sense of humor.

97
00:05:34.101 --> 00:05:36.801
Or those pesky ten pounds.

98
00:05:38.439 --> 00:05:40.917
Mrs. Petrillo. is that you?

99
00:05:40.941 --> 00:05:43.574
No. it's Jane Fonda.

100
00:05:45.179 --> 00:05:47.023
Come on. Give us a hug.

101
00:05:47.047 --> 00:05:50.092
Aw. Trudy. it's so
good to see you again.

102
00:05:50.116 --> 00:05:52.762
Honey. meet my roommates
- Rose and Blanche.

103
00:05:52.786 --> 00:05:55.832
It's a pleasure. Dorothy's
told us so much about you.

104
00:05:55.856 --> 00:05:57.266
All good. I hope.

105
00:05:57.290 --> 00:05:59.123
Well. actually... Sit!

106
00:06:02.762 --> 00:06:05.709
Well. finally I get to meet
the infamous Dorothy.

107
00:06:05.733 --> 00:06:07.977
Boy. has Trudy told me
stories about you two.

108
00:06:08.001 --> 00:06:11.514
I'll bet she has. We had such a
great time back in high school.

109
00:06:11.538 --> 00:06:16.252
Like the time you and Trudy ran
against each other for class treasurer?

110
00:06:16.276 --> 00:06:18.254
You know. back in St. Olaf.

111
00:06:18.278 --> 00:06:21.846
I ran for president of
the Bull Castration Club.

112
00:06:26.754 --> 00:06:29.866
There is no sound in this
world sweeter than a bull's moo

113
00:06:29.890 --> 00:06:32.223
as it climbs an octave.

114
00:06:34.594 --> 00:06:35.572
Did you win?

115
00:06:35.596 --> 00:06:37.996
No. Lost by a hair.

116
00:06:40.768 --> 00:06:43.245
I admired you after
that loss. Dorothy.

117
00:06:43.269 --> 00:06:47.150
You just picked up
the pieces and went on.

118
00:06:47.174 --> 00:06:50.942
Just like you did after Stanley
ran off with that stewardess.

119
00:06:51.945 --> 00:06:53.923
Boy. I envy you your gumption.

120
00:06:53.947 --> 00:06:56.748
And I your breast implants.

121
00:06:59.086 --> 00:07:01.364
This may not be my place.

122
00:07:01.388 --> 00:07:05.201
but you two hardly
sound like old friends.

123
00:07:05.225 --> 00:07:07.770
Blanche is right. We
should be more positive.

124
00:07:07.794 --> 00:07:10.673
Dorothy. you look wonderful. Ah.

125
00:07:10.697 --> 00:07:14.577
The left one turned out nice.

126
00:07:14.601 --> 00:07:17.447
Dorothy! Oh. come on.
Rose. I'm just kidding.

127
00:07:17.471 --> 00:07:20.483
They're both practically
the same size.

128
00:07:20.507 --> 00:07:22.952
How about giving me
a hand in the kitchen?

129
00:07:22.976 --> 00:07:25.288
Were they like that in
high school. Mrs. Petrillo?

130
00:07:25.312 --> 00:07:28.346
Oh. no. Her breasts were
actually a lot smaller back then.

131
00:07:31.018 --> 00:07:33.329
I meant. were they rivals?

132
00:07:33.353 --> 00:07:37.434
What is this -<i> Nova?</i> I
don't have all the answers.

133
00:07:37.458 --> 00:07:40.737
I'm afraid you'll have
to excuse Sophia. Jack.

134
00:07:40.761 --> 00:07:42.960
Oh. You heard that?

135
00:07:50.704 --> 00:07:54.439
I thought I was safe backed
up against these pillows.

136
00:07:58.745 --> 00:08:01.357
Why don't we see what's
keeping Trudy and Dorothy?

137
00:08:01.381 --> 00:08:03.526
Probably got caught
up reminiscing.

138
00:08:03.550 --> 00:08:05.961
You know how it is when
old pals get together.

139
00:08:05.985 --> 00:08:07.685
Excuse us.

140
00:08:16.797 --> 00:08:18.140
Well. that's that.

141
00:08:18.164 --> 00:08:20.710
How does it feel to
have your butt whipped?

142
00:08:20.734 --> 00:08:24.869
Well. sometimes I find it
strangely titillating. but...

143
00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:29.340
Oh! You were talking to her.

144
00:08:32.312 --> 00:08:35.158
Trudy. how about if
tomorrow we play a real game?

145
00:08:35.182 --> 00:08:37.393
Something that
requires real skill.

146
00:08:37.417 --> 00:08:40.463
You mean like
midget ice bowling?

147
00:08:40.487 --> 00:08:44.934
I'm talking about
tennis. you doofus.

148
00:08:44.958 --> 00:08:47.837
Aren't you afraid of being
humiliated on the tennis court?

149
00:08:47.861 --> 00:08:50.005
Me humiliated?

150
00:08:50.029 --> 00:08:53.042
I think you forget. Trudy. we
have to wear tennis dresses.

151
00:08:53.066 --> 00:08:56.112
You're on. you pathetic
middle-aged cow.

152
00:08:56.136 --> 00:09:01.017
I am looking forward to it.
you miserable sack of cellulite.

153
00:09:01.041 --> 00:09:04.654
Did I tell you that Larry
Prowse called the other day?

154
00:09:04.678 --> 00:09:07.390
Really? Did he ever get
married? Three times.

155
00:09:07.414 --> 00:09:10.781
Actually four. if
you count Victor.

156
00:09:25.665 --> 00:09:27.210
Can you believe it?

157
00:09:27.234 --> 00:09:29.212
Two women competing like that.

158
00:09:29.236 --> 00:09:32.514
and there's not
even a man at stake.

159
00:09:32.538 --> 00:09:34.584
In Sicily. women
compete for everything.

160
00:09:34.608 --> 00:09:39.288
The most famous example is the
Great String-Cheese War of '47.

161
00:09:39.312 --> 00:09:41.390
But why should I
bore you with that?

162
00:09:41.414 --> 00:09:43.960
You all have college
credits. You took history.

163
00:09:43.984 --> 00:09:47.263
Sophia. have you been
out in the hot sun too long?

164
00:09:47.287 --> 00:09:51.455
It's a possibility. Is there
wax running out of my ears?

165
00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:57.507
Boy. Trudy is beating
the dickens out of Dorothy.

166
00:09:57.531 --> 00:10:02.445
Oh... I just have
to... catch my breath.

167
00:10:02.469 --> 00:10:06.081
Are we gonna play. or do
you wanna forfeit? No way.

168
00:10:06.105 --> 00:10:09.852
No. Dorothy Zbornak doesn't know
the meaning of the word "forfeit."

169
00:10:09.876 --> 00:10:13.010
And she's a teacher. too.

170
00:10:14.314 --> 00:10:17.415
No wonder the
Japanese are ahead of us.

171
00:10:19.019 --> 00:10:21.530
I'm gonna kill you. Trudy.

172
00:10:21.554 --> 00:10:24.434
Oh. do you really think
she can make a comeback?

173
00:10:24.458 --> 00:10:26.435
I'm sure she can.

174
00:10:26.459 --> 00:10:28.871
Dorothy's running
Trudy all over the court.

175
00:10:28.895 --> 00:10:31.474
Oh. Trudy tripped.

176
00:10:31.498 --> 00:10:35.111
And she's not getting up.
You think something's wrong?

177
00:10:35.135 --> 00:10:36.846
I think she's fainted.

178
00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:39.381
I hope it's not anything worse.

179
00:10:39.405 --> 00:10:41.985
It is. I've seen that look
before. You don't think...?

180
00:10:42.009 --> 00:10:45.087
There are two things in
this world a Sicilian knows.

181
00:10:45.111 --> 00:10:47.156
When pasta sticks
to a wall. it's done.

182
00:10:47.180 --> 00:10:50.415
When a body sticks
to cement. it's dead.

183
00:11:00.661 --> 00:11:04.607
Why did it have to happen
this way? I feel like a murderer!

184
00:11:04.631 --> 00:11:06.609
I will not hear any
more of that nonsense.

185
00:11:06.633 --> 00:11:09.145
It was a freak occurrence
on a tennis court.

186
00:11:09.169 --> 00:11:12.481
She's right. Dorothy.
You did nothing wrong.

187
00:11:12.505 --> 00:11:15.473
Technically. I mean. nothing
that would hold up in a court of law.

188
00:11:20.213 --> 00:11:21.591
But why Trudy?

189
00:11:21.615 --> 00:11:25.661
She was the most energetic.
alive person I ever knew.

190
00:11:25.685 --> 00:11:28.464
At the Center. Dorothy.
we teach acceptance.

191
00:11:28.488 --> 00:11:32.235
In life. some things are inevitable.
and you just have to accept them.

192
00:11:32.259 --> 00:11:35.638
She is right. Dorothy. I know
because I've been there myself.

193
00:11:35.662 --> 00:11:39.608
You killed your best
friend. too. Blanche?

194
00:11:39.632 --> 00:11:41.009
Sorry. Dorothy.

195
00:11:41.033 --> 00:11:43.446
I remember I was
a blossoming belle

196
00:11:43.470 --> 00:11:45.781
who had just won the Little
Miss Magnolia Pageant.

197
00:11:45.805 --> 00:11:47.950
Blanche. before you start.

198
00:11:47.974 --> 00:11:51.053
realize I am very vulnerable now

199
00:11:51.077 --> 00:11:53.388
and in no mood to
hear a story about you

200
00:11:53.412 --> 00:11:57.093
and some yahoo cracker
with four first names

201
00:11:57.117 --> 00:12:00.451
pawing at each other
under a magnolia tree.

202
00:12:05.992 --> 00:12:08.538
Well. pardon me. Dorothy. but...

203
00:12:08.562 --> 00:12:12.630
we can't all come from places
as socially acceptable as Brooklyn.

204
00:12:14.935 --> 00:12:17.980
I'm sorry. Blanche.
Go on with the story.

205
00:12:18.004 --> 00:12:24.308
Just try to shy away from words
like "tarnation" and "catfish."

206
00:12:25.712 --> 00:12:27.890
Fine.

207
00:12:27.914 --> 00:12:29.892
Anyway. I was
about eight years old

208
00:12:29.916 --> 00:12:32.428
when I first met Cathy
Lee on the playground.

209
00:12:32.452 --> 00:12:35.497
We became fast friends.

210
00:12:35.521 --> 00:12:38.467
just as thick as Louisiana
blackstrap molasses

211
00:12:38.491 --> 00:12:41.871
on a stake of johnnycakes
as high as an elephant's knee...

212
00:12:41.895 --> 00:12:45.007
On a riverboat floating
down the Mississippi delta.

213
00:12:45.031 --> 00:12:48.232
Finish the damn story. Blanche!

214
00:12:51.037 --> 00:12:54.316
Anyway. it was at our
Southern seafood fry

215
00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:57.086
that I proudly dragged Cathy
Lee over to meet my folks.

216
00:12:57.110 --> 00:12:59.088
My mama took one
look at Cathy Lee

217
00:12:59.112 --> 00:13:01.357
and forbad me ever
to see her again.

218
00:13:01.381 --> 00:13:03.326
Why?

219
00:13:03.350 --> 00:13:05.861
Because her mother was not in
the Daughters of the Confederacy.

220
00:13:05.885 --> 00:13:09.865
Oh! How my heart went
out to little Cathy Lee.

221
00:13:09.889 --> 00:13:14.803
standing there while our
servants snickered at her servants.

222
00:13:14.827 --> 00:13:17.540
But Mama insisted I
break off the friendship.

223
00:13:17.564 --> 00:13:21.410
or I wouldn't get brand-new
riding boots for Christmas.

224
00:13:21.434 --> 00:13:22.945
So I did.

225
00:13:22.969 --> 00:13:26.682
Blanche. why is this a
story about acceptance?

226
00:13:26.706 --> 00:13:28.985
Because years later.
to get back at me.

227
00:13:29.009 --> 00:13:31.509
Cathy Lee slept with my daddy.

228
00:13:37.150 --> 00:13:40.084
That was something
I had to accept.

229
00:13:42.421 --> 00:13:45.400
Mama accepted it. too.

230
00:13:45.424 --> 00:13:49.994
Along with a brand-new
Cadillac Eldorado for her birthday.

231
00:13:52.031 --> 00:13:54.410
You know. my family
had a few dollars.

232
00:13:54.434 --> 00:13:56.645
and I loved them dearly.

233
00:13:56.669 --> 00:14:00.939
but when you get right down
to it. basically. they were trash.

234
00:14:07.447 --> 00:14:11.393
Don't worry. Dorothy. The
reunion'll get your mind off of it.

235
00:14:11.417 --> 00:14:13.628
People should be coming
in a couple of hours.

236
00:14:13.652 --> 00:14:16.665
The party. The
party! I totally forgot!

237
00:14:16.689 --> 00:14:18.734
There is no way I
can face those people.

238
00:14:18.758 --> 00:14:21.636
Honey. of course you can.
You were all friends of Trudy's.

239
00:14:21.660 --> 00:14:24.773
You can console each
other. It'll help you to cope.

240
00:14:24.797 --> 00:14:26.776
Maybe this is just what I need.

241
00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:28.944
Aw. yeah. Good for you. Dorothy.

242
00:14:28.968 --> 00:14:32.715
Of course. breaking
the news will not be easy.

243
00:14:32.739 --> 00:14:35.818
Want my advice? Wait a
couple of hours before you do.

244
00:14:35.842 --> 00:14:40.277
Stuff like this can put a
real damper on happy hour.

245
00:14:53.894 --> 00:14:56.638
And listen. Rose.
remember. mum's the word.

246
00:14:56.662 --> 00:14:59.876
Dorothy will break the
bad news in due time. OK?

247
00:14:59.900 --> 00:15:02.978
Excuse me. Has
anyone seen Dorothy?

248
00:15:03.002 --> 00:15:05.380
She said hello and
then disappeared.

249
00:15:05.404 --> 00:15:07.116
Is there a problem?

250
00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:11.020
No! No problem at
all. Everything's fine.

251
00:15:11.044 --> 00:15:13.484
It's not like anyone
died or anything.

252
00:15:17.584 --> 00:15:20.729
It's so good to see everyone.

253
00:15:20.753 --> 00:15:24.666
But where's Trudy? She
hasn't seen me in years.

254
00:15:24.690 --> 00:15:28.104
I can't wait to see
the look on her face.

255
00:15:28.128 --> 00:15:30.828
You could wait six
months. it wouldn't change.

256
00:15:33.533 --> 00:15:36.912
It's been almost two hours.
We can't keep up this charade.

257
00:15:36.936 --> 00:15:40.149
Somebody has got to get Dorothy
to come out and break the news.

258
00:15:40.173 --> 00:15:44.386
But she's so fragile now. We have
to be tender and compassionate.

259
00:15:44.410 --> 00:15:47.890
kindly and sympathetic and
caring and understanding...

260
00:15:47.914 --> 00:15:50.615
Stop babbling. you
yutz. I'll do it. I'll do it.

261
00:15:54.154 --> 00:15:58.033
Picture it - Sicily. 1852.

262
00:15:58.057 --> 00:15:59.869
Ma. I am in no mood.

263
00:15:59.893 --> 00:16:02.738
And besides. you
weren't alive in 1852.

264
00:16:02.762 --> 00:16:04.707
What? We can't
learn from history?

265
00:16:04.731 --> 00:16:06.475
It was mid-century

266
00:16:06.499 --> 00:16:10.046
and a disillusioned Italy looked to
the house of Savoy for leadership.

267
00:16:10.070 --> 00:16:15.451
Giuseppe Garibaldi. our courageous
leader. and not a bad dresser.

268
00:16:15.475 --> 00:16:18.220
thought. "Let's regain
some national pride

269
00:16:18.244 --> 00:16:22.524
and jump into this
Crimean War thing."

270
00:16:22.548 --> 00:16:25.928
Of course. there was a big kickoff
party at Giuseppe's beach house.

271
00:16:25.952 --> 00:16:27.996
and everyone came.

272
00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:30.532
Coincidentally. this
was also the night

273
00:16:30.556 --> 00:16:34.392
his wife Rosa hit
her sexual peak.

274
00:16:37.897 --> 00:16:40.575
Ma. I am in here
because of guilt.

275
00:16:40.599 --> 00:16:43.012
This is not a story about guilt.

276
00:16:43.036 --> 00:16:47.082
This is a story about
being a bad hostess.

277
00:16:47.106 --> 00:16:49.451
While Rosa had
Giuseppe in the bedroom

278
00:16:49.475 --> 00:16:52.054
with his saber
around his ankles.

279
00:16:52.078 --> 00:16:53.622
200 hungry guests

280
00:16:53.646 --> 00:16:58.727
were strip-searching
mice for a piece of cheese.

281
00:16:58.751 --> 00:17:02.431
Ma. so what's your point? That
Rosa and I throw bad parties?

282
00:17:02.455 --> 00:17:04.333
That's my minor point.

283
00:17:04.357 --> 00:17:07.970
My major point is that. like Rosa.
you're screwing around in the bedroom

284
00:17:07.994 --> 00:17:11.028
when there are important
things to do outside.

285
00:17:14.066 --> 00:17:17.046
I can't believe it.
That makes sense.

286
00:17:17.070 --> 00:17:19.448
I mean. you went the
long way around but...

287
00:17:19.472 --> 00:17:22.685
that actually makes sense.

288
00:17:22.709 --> 00:17:26.288
Look. pussycat. your friends
deserve to know about Trudy.

289
00:17:26.312 --> 00:17:29.792
And they'll understand.
because they are your friends.

290
00:17:29.816 --> 00:17:31.348
Oh. Ma. Ma. thanks.

291
00:17:33.219 --> 00:17:37.188
Well... here goes.

292
00:17:45.298 --> 00:17:46.575
Everybody...

293
00:17:46.599 --> 00:17:49.245
Everybody. can I have
your attention. please?

294
00:17:49.269 --> 00:17:51.813
Uh...

295
00:17:51.837 --> 00:17:56.618
I know I've been a bit scarce
tonight. but there is a reason.

296
00:17:56.642 --> 00:17:59.789
Something tragic
happened this morning.

297
00:17:59.813 --> 00:18:01.790
Oh. Ma. I need your help.

298
00:18:01.814 --> 00:18:03.892
Sure. sweetheart.

299
00:18:03.916 --> 00:18:06.316
Trudy's dead.

300
00:18:13.960 --> 00:18:15.938
Please. everybody.

301
00:18:15.962 --> 00:18:18.796
It happened this morning
when we were playing tennis.

302
00:18:19.999 --> 00:18:22.478
Trudy's heart just
couldn't take it.

303
00:18:22.502 --> 00:18:25.947
I'm so sorry that I dragged
her out on the court

304
00:18:25.971 --> 00:18:29.752
and made her run
back and forth so hard.

305
00:18:29.776 --> 00:18:31.920
I wish it had been
me instead of her.

306
00:18:31.944 --> 00:18:34.222
because it's all my fault.

307
00:18:34.246 --> 00:18:36.592
We might as well
take down that banner

308
00:18:36.616 --> 00:18:41.919
and put up one that says. "Welcome
to the Dorothy Killed Trudy Party"!

309
00:18:47.026 --> 00:18:49.371
Oh. darn. Someone's late.

310
00:18:49.395 --> 00:18:53.130
Dorothy'll have to give
her speech all over again.

311
00:18:56.336 --> 00:18:57.976
Hi. everybody!

312
00:18:59.105 --> 00:19:00.348
Trudy?

313
00:19:00.372 --> 00:19:02.384
I don't believe
this. Is that you?

314
00:19:02.408 --> 00:19:03.986
In the flesh.

315
00:19:04.010 --> 00:19:07.123
Yeah. but I can't
believe you're really here!

316
00:19:07.147 --> 00:19:09.191
I don't understand!
How did you...?

317
00:19:09.215 --> 00:19:13.862
It was all staged. Rose. A patented
Trudy McMann practical joke.

318
00:19:16.022 --> 00:19:18.333
Well. I don't find
that one bit funny.

319
00:19:18.357 --> 00:19:20.336
It was cruel. Trudy.

320
00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:24.306
Come on! It was just a practical
joke like we did in high school.

321
00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:26.508
Some of the things
we did in high school

322
00:19:26.532 --> 00:19:29.578
are not necessarily
appropriate when we're adults.

323
00:19:29.602 --> 00:19:32.014
Like staying up all night
and carousing around.

324
00:19:32.038 --> 00:19:34.604
dating every other man you meet.

325
00:19:37.376 --> 00:19:39.743
I'm losing credibility
here. aren't I?

326
00:19:42.215 --> 00:19:44.693
Trudy. you did a
very cruel thing.

327
00:19:46.318 --> 00:19:49.365
OK. OK. If I went
too far. I'm sorry.

328
00:19:49.389 --> 00:19:53.624
Maybe you ought to apologize to
Dorothy. She's back in her bedroom.

329
00:19:57.897 --> 00:20:01.576
Uh. Dorothy? Are you all right?

330
00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:03.645
Go away.

331
00:20:03.669 --> 00:20:07.549
Dorothy. honey. it's
Rose. We need to talk.

332
00:20:07.573 --> 00:20:09.885
I said go away.

333
00:20:09.909 --> 00:20:11.620
Leave it to me.

334
00:20:11.644 --> 00:20:14.957
In a few minutes. I'll have
her beaming from ear to ear.

335
00:20:30.529 --> 00:20:32.341
Oh. my God! Trudy!

336
00:20:32.365 --> 00:20:33.842
Dorothy!

337
00:20:33.866 --> 00:20:35.411
Jack!

338
00:20:35.435 --> 00:20:37.045
How come you're alive?

339
00:20:37.069 --> 00:20:39.114
How come you're in
bed with my husband?

340
00:20:39.138 --> 00:20:41.951
I asked you first.

341
00:20:41.975 --> 00:20:43.752
Honey. it's not
what it looks like.

342
00:20:43.776 --> 00:20:48.256
Obviously. Dorothy thought I
was dead. tried to comfort you.

343
00:20:48.280 --> 00:20:50.392
and the two of you
got carried away.

344
00:20:50.416 --> 00:20:52.894
OK. it is what it looks like.

345
00:20:52.918 --> 00:20:56.698
I can't believe this. I
was just playing a prank.

346
00:20:56.722 --> 00:20:59.234
Do you have any idea how I feel?

347
00:20:59.258 --> 00:21:00.468
What kind of person

348
00:21:00.492 --> 00:21:02.871
jumps into bed with her
dearest friend's husband?

349
00:21:02.895 --> 00:21:06.530
Not necessarily a bad person.
Sometimes circumstances...

350
00:21:08.067 --> 00:21:11.035
Oh. You were talking about her.

351
00:21:13.306 --> 00:21:15.417
I think I'm gonna faint.

352
00:21:15.441 --> 00:21:18.643
Gotcha!

353
00:21:24.250 --> 00:21:27.363
Dorothy. what the
hell is going on here?

354
00:21:27.387 --> 00:21:29.164
Revenge!

355
00:21:29.188 --> 00:21:32.935
It suddenly occurred to me - what if
this was the ultimate practical joke?

356
00:21:32.959 --> 00:21:37.172
So I dragged it out of Jack. and
the two of us cooked up this topper.

357
00:21:37.196 --> 00:21:39.742
Jack. I can't believe
you went along with this.

358
00:21:39.766 --> 00:21:42.711
So I got in bed with
Dorothy. It was a joke!

359
00:21:42.735 --> 00:21:44.935
Don't even think it. Ma.

360
00:21:46.773 --> 00:21:49.351
If you knew before.
why didn't you tell me?

361
00:21:49.375 --> 00:21:51.420
Ma. you have a big mouth.

362
00:21:51.444 --> 00:21:53.188
Me? If I had a big mouth.

363
00:21:53.212 --> 00:21:55.023
do you think your one-night
stand with the bug man

364
00:21:55.047 --> 00:21:57.214
would still be a secret?

365
00:21:58.751 --> 00:22:01.330
Oops.

366
00:22:01.354 --> 00:22:04.766
Dorothy Zbornak. this
is the most underhanded.

367
00:22:04.790 --> 00:22:08.370
sneaky practical joke
anyone has ever made.

368
00:22:08.394 --> 00:22:11.140
and I have just
one thing to say.

369
00:22:11.164 --> 00:22:13.442
Boy. have I missed you!

370
00:22:13.466 --> 00:22:16.544
Oh. Trudy... Trudy!

371
00:22:16.568 --> 00:22:19.915
I've missed you. too.

372
00:22:19.939 --> 00:22:23.786
Wait just a minute.
You two are not mad?

373
00:22:23.810 --> 00:22:27.690
Are you kidding? Our friendship
was built on years of this.

374
00:22:27.714 --> 00:22:31.660
Trudy. you have made
this one hell of a reunion.

375
00:22:31.684 --> 00:22:36.231
Speaking of which. there's
a party out there. Come on!

376
00:22:36.255 --> 00:22:40.869
Well. Dorothy Zbornak. I cannot
believe you put Rose and me through this.

377
00:22:40.893 --> 00:22:42.070
Yeah!

378
00:22:42.094 --> 00:22:43.872
What are you talking about?

379
00:22:43.896 --> 00:22:46.641
You knew Trudy was playing
a practical joke all along.

380
00:22:46.665 --> 00:22:48.911
and you never shared
it with your best friends?

381
00:22:48.935 --> 00:22:50.779
We thought you were devastated.

382
00:22:50.803 --> 00:22:53.148
We suffered right
along with you. Yeah!

383
00:22:53.172 --> 00:22:55.217
That was insensitive.
Insensitive!

384
00:22:55.241 --> 00:22:56.452
Selfish. Selfish!

385
00:22:56.476 --> 00:22:58.420
As far as we are
concerned. Dorothy Zbornak.

386
00:22:58.444 --> 00:23:00.422
you have gone too far this time.

387
00:23:00.446 --> 00:23:03.792
No. This is unforgivable. We are
never gonna speak to you again.

388
00:23:03.816 --> 00:23:05.282
Right!

389
00:23:10.756 --> 00:23:11.756
Gotcha.

390
00:23:16.963 --> 00:23:20.175
Very. very convincing. Blanche.

391
00:23:20.199 --> 00:23:23.900
I can't take all the credit. I did
have some help. Right. Rose?

392
00:23:26.405 --> 00:23:28.272
Rose?

393
00:23:29.275 --> 00:23:31.308
Rose?
